ai_story_gen.1.player.story: Becky knew she wasn't supposed to take her father's boat out of the harbour onto the open sea by herself, but it was a lovely day and the sea was still and calm, she'd watched her father operate the boat more times than she could remember so she felt confident as she started the motor and headed out.      Becky turned her face upwards towards the warm sun and closed her eyes, blissfully enjoying the heat and the sound of the water lapping at the sides of the boat.   She felt a shadow pass overhead and opened her eyes, delighted to see the seagull flying over her head and the three others who had joined their brother, she felt giddy as they circled above her with their shrieking cries. Suddenly one of the gulls swooped lower and she felt a stabbing pain in her head as it's beak connected with it, another beak flew into her face and she screamed as she felt her flesh tear. Beak after razor-sharp beak pecked at her head and slashed her arms as she tried to protect herself. Blood was running down her face into her eyes and she could no longer see.   She curled into a ball at the bottom of the boat and waited for the onslaught to stop, and she waited and she waited and she waited. By mid-afternoon the next day an empty boat was seen gently drifting into the harbour.
follow_up.2.player.spark: Probably Alfred Hitchcock's 'The Birds'.

ai_story_gen.1.player.story: John, an explorer and adventurer, had a lifelong ambition to enter the mysterious jungle where nobody before him had survived, and at long last he embarked on his mission to seek the legendary lost city of Perditum.  During the first few days of his adventure, John acclimatised himself with the jungle, seeking out safe vegetation to eat, building makeshift shelters along the way and keeping out of the way of dangerous animals.  After two weeks of pushing deeper into the jungle, he stumbled upon a settlement of mudhuts, where he saw  groups of native women, some cooking food over fires, some sitting by the river washing clothes, as they watched their children playing happily in the distance.  Suddenly one of the women started screaming hysterically and it soon became clear that her child was missing; John ran across to the group, who, startled at first at seeing a stranger in their midst, desperately pointed to an area of dense undergrowth behind the huts.  It became clear that the child had been seen running towards the undergrowth, but when John ventured in that direction, the women tried to stop him, looks of sheer terror on their faces, and emitting bloodcurdling screams as he ignored their warnings and ran towards the deep undergrowth.  As he ventured further, the jungle became thicker, and after two hours of struggling through the dense growth, sustaining cuts and bruises and being bitten by insects, he stumbled, falling and hitting his head on a stump, whereupon he passed out.  As he regained consciousness, he remembered a vivid dream that he must have experienced whilst unconscious, where he was floundering in a swamp, desperately trying to get out, before succumbing to the abyss; when suddenly a small boy appeared from nowhere and miraculously pulled him to safety, after which, John knew he had to carry on and find the missing boy.  He got to his feet and staggered on, gradually becoming stronger, when suddenly a clearing appeared in the jungle, and John could hardly believe what he was witnessing: the long lost city he had set out to discover, and here was the missing boy, looking bewildered and lost; John hauled him up onto his shoulders and began the long journey back to the safety of the boy's home village.

ai_story_gen.1.player.story: We last saw our plane three days ago, when we crashed through the dense jungle foliage 150 miles from our destination. Since then I and my two friends have been trekking through the uncharted landscape, heat and humidity driving us mad, fierce wild animals a threat we all fear round every twisting tree and tangled vine. Nightfall draws near, and it's then that our luck seems to change; in the distance a gentle glowing light shines through the emerald leaves, and with the last of our energy we stumble towards it. What greets us as we part through the thinning jungle is a settlement, an indigenous village we'd never even heard of, people appearing one by one from their woven wooden homes to investigate our arrival. We tense, my friend reaching for something in his backpack but I stay his hand. Only when the people seem appeased can we finally draw our next calm breath - and our pacificity had been worth it. Through jumbled signs and gestures that last through much of the evening, we finally communicate our troubles, and the people begin to point all in one direction, East of here, and following their guidance we make it back to recognised civilisation. For the rest of our lives not one of us shared a word of the people who saved us, not daring to bring the horrors of modernity down upon their peaceful village.

ai_story_gen.1.player.story: I've always wanted to partake in an adventure on the open seas and surprisingly the opportunity arose just last year. I'd booked and embarked a fairly bog standard 2 week sailing holiday touring the Greek Islands during the summer months last year. There was myself and 5 other guests on the boat together with the captain and two other crew members responsible for the day to day running of the boat and keeping their paying passengers happy. All was proceeding as planned and we'd already enjoyed some leisurely sailing initially setting sail from Athens and touring the Greek mainland coast two days and two nights before heading into more adventurous waters. The plan was to head toward Santorini and we were well on our way until the fourth night of the trip where we encountered the most amazing an colourful storm the like of which I have never seen before. As we were engulfed by the storm the boat was lifted out of the water and we found ourselves bashed and buffeted towards an island which worryingly the captain informed us did not appear on any maps and to make matters worse the storm had made out boat no longer seaworthy and knocked out all of our communications and navigation equipment. We set up camp on the island as best we could with what we could extract from our damaged boat but what was even stranger we were not alone on the island - it would appear that we were sharing the island with a colony of 6 foot tall chickens. So we're still there now three months later but things have not been too bad with a plentiful supply of massive eggs but I'm afraid we're all starting to get very sick of the meals consisting of mainly omelette and scrambled eggs to the quicker you can rescue us from where we've ended up as a result of our open seas adventure I'd be extremely grateful!

The interweaving cycles of Short Day and Long Day and Night had played havoc with their sleep patterns. Without the welcoming, gentle  diplomacy of the Blue People. they were sure they would have fallen foul of the more belligerent inhabitants, in their weakened and confused state. As things had progressed toward what they now thought of as the "new normal" of life on the planet, it gradually, though slowly, became apparent that there were complications in the relations between the different sentient species, which they would never fully understand, and must be very careful to tread around. This, of course, is to be expected in all first contact scenarios, and was a major focus of their training, but it is recognised that the particular nuances of a given situation can never be foreseen, or fully comprehended, Caution and humility are absolutely crucial, and yet, in spite of meticulous training and selection of participants, unpredictable difficulties always arise.     Thus, I could not be surprised to learn of the perilous conditions which had developed over the course of that first World-Year (which I must remind you, is equivalent to almost three Earth-years); on the contrary, I must commend the unit for the tenacity and astuteness with which they were able to navigate the relationships, such that there is now a flourishing and mutually beneficial alliance between the parties. The peaceful conditions which now prevail have enabled the unit to pursue their research and develop a broader knowledge of the various inhabitants, which I shall describe in as much detail as possible in this report.

ai_story_gen.1.player.story: Stephen, the Captain, completed his pre-flight checks and after a brief pause commenced his take off.  Looking ahead he could see the relative motion of the spaceship as his surroundings the launch pad superstructure, the control point buildings and the direct communication bridges and the seemed to be going backwards past him.  The vibrations of the space craft as it set out on its inter-stella voyage seemed somehow soothing, but Stephen wondered how long it would be before they became annoying.  He glanced at the pursers display - showing the stocks carried for the long journey ahead and wondered at the range of items he new was included for use on voyages such as this.  Suddenly a loud series of alerts alarms sounded, lots of lights and the vessel began to shake violently, the helper computers display flickered and then steadied - showing the death sentence of all space vehicles - fatal fuel leak, commence abandon ship procedures.  Stephen hit the eject button to shoot the self powered people pod away from the now doomed spaceship - the failure having taken place too soon after takeoff for any other such manoeuvring - and saw with satisfaction the display telling him the pod was away on its controlled landing.  Hitting the control to use the remaining power to guide the wreck to crash onto a safe landing spot, and commenced the final abandonment of the now barely in control ship Stephen sat back to wait.  Well done said a voice in his ear - you passed the simulator again - as Stephen smiled to himself and hoped it would never happen for real.

ai_story_gen.1.player.story: It was late December when a group of fearless explorers decided to set sail on the open seas in search of the legendary lost treasure of the pirate king named Silver Sword. Once they set sail they encountered many challenges that almost led to them giving up including a fierce storm, which nearly sank the ship, and also an encounter with a huge sea creature a massive octopus which dragged a few of the group into the ocean where they drowned. They continued to travel across the sea and overcame the storms and sea creature through team work, managing to navigate the rough seas, storms and escaping the beast until they reached their final destination. Though perseverance the remaining group reached the mysterious island and made their way towards the location of the treasure marked on the map, excited to uncover the treasure that had been lost for centuries and which would make the losses and difficulties encountered worthwhile. They made their way across the island when they found a massive structure which looked like a castle with a door with symbols on it, the symbols were mentioned on the back of the map and explorers found that they had to move these symbols in a certain pattern to open the door which they did. The door opened and there was a massive room and in the center was gold as far as the eye could see and diamond, rubies and emeralds, the explorer were filled with joy and happiness that they had reached their goal and discovered the treasure. One of the explorers picked up a piece of gold which immediately triggered a trap- the door closed behind them and out came a giant dragon, they knew that there was no escape and that this would be their final resting place, despite their best efforts to fight back the dragon killed them all and the legendary treasure remains hidden to this day- a warning to those that greed can lead to death.

ai_story_gen.1.player.story: Bob and Alice are playing on the beach one day when they spot a small wooden boat at the water's edge. There are two paddles inside and Alice suggests to Bob that they get in the boat and take it out on the water, Bob is unsure "it might be dangerous" he says to Alice, but Alice dares him to do it so he agrees and they push the boat out in to the water and get in it. Paddling furiously against the incoming waves their excitement gets the better of them and by the time they stop to look back they are a long way from the shore. "I'm scared," Alice says to Bob, "we should turn back now", but Bob is excited now and says "no, let's keep padding and see how far we can get". A few minutes later the shore is now so distant it is hardly visible and even Bob is starting to get a bit scared so they agree to turn back but it is too late, the boat is caught it a strong current and is being drawn further from the shore; even paddling as fast as they can, Bob and Alice cannot make progress against the current and as their arms tire they stop padding and just let the boat drift where it will. As it starts to go dark the temperature drops and they huddle together to keep warm, wondering where they will end up as tiredness gets the better of them and they start nod off. Suddenly they are woken from their semi-sleep by a loud noise and a lurching of the boat and realise they have hit something; Bob gropes around by the side of the boat and feels hard rock: "Quick Alice, we've hit land, let's get out of the boat!" They climb out on to the rock and feel their way up away from the water, relieved to be on land but wondering where on earth they have ended up.

However, trouble wasn't far behind when Captain Bilby's pet cat, Disco, tottered out of the shuttlecraft, having crept on to be part of the adventure! It turned out that the Zarglings didn't know what cats were, and thought the Captain had unleased a dangerous creature! Captain Bilby managed to explain the situation, whilst Disco looked on, completely oblivious to the diplomatic incident he'd nearly caused. The Zargling ambassador kindly offered Disco some of their local delicacy, baked He'Dash, a type of meat, and Disco wasted no time in eating the offered snack. The Zargling diplomats were very smitten with Disco, and wanted to pet him and watch his strange feline ways. Thanks in no small part to the Captain's cat, the diplomatic negotiations were a complete success, with Disco even being awarded the Zargling Medal of Freedom - their highest honour!
follow_up.2.player.spark: I am a massive sci-fi fan so this is an amalgam from things like Star Trek, Babylon 5, The Expanse and my own imagination.
payment.1.player.comments: I had a lot of fun writing that story, but deliberately steered away from any dark or more adult themes to keep it light, amusing and short.

ai_story_gen.1.player.story: Sarah's brother, Ted, had always wanted to be a sailor and dreamed of sailing across from Europe to the Caribbean. When Ted died tragically after falling off his bike, Sarah found a map he had drawn when he was thirteen detailing the journey he would make when he was twenty-one. As Sarah approached her twennty-first birthday, she decided she would complete the voyage in memory of Ted and acquired a boat which she named Teddy's Dream. Setting out from Portugal, she set sail into the open seas, with Ted's map, for a journey that would take her four months. At first, the seas were calm and she found the experience enjoyable and easy. But three weeks into the trip, she started experiencing problems and when a storm blew in, it damaged part of the boat and knocked out all communication. Sarah was left drifting on the seas in a damaged boat and without any way of calling for help. Just when Sarah was beginning to worry about what might happen to her, a humpbacked whale breached the sea next to her and seemed to be directing her onwards, it was then that Sarah remembered Ted's favourite animal was a humpback whale and she followed the animal as it led her to the Caribbean.

From the gas clouds, crystalline rain, down to the plants and even the soil, it was like Sarah was a newborn exploring how the world worked with no frame of reference. Luckily, the creatures that inhabited the planet were not either incredibly hostile nor completely afraid as was the norm on planetary excursions, and she was able to live a peaceful coexistence with them. Over some time, this coexistence became a friendship, and an understanding of their communication through much trial and error meant that Sarah was able to become a part of their society. This society then revealed their most pressing need; the recovery of their ancient orb which had been lost in tribal warfare many centuries ago, that was crucial for the true succession of a ruler to unify their people. Sarah agreed to find this orb using the technological advances granted to her by the remainder of her original flight suit, and what was salvageable from the craft that was now slowly becoming part of the jungle. After much searching, the orb was located in the bowels of a deep chasm in the jungle, where a breakaway tribe guarded it with a simple demand: if Sarah was willing to take her life, the orb would be returned to its original resting place.
